**1. Label Conventions**

Labels are the human-facing names for nodes. They appear in the research
tool, the visualization, and the API. The label conventions exist to
prevent display collisions, ensure consistency, and make the graph
legible to contributors and users.

Core rule: no two nodes across any type may share a display label. The
validator enforces this.

**1.1 Label convention by node type**

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Node Type**                 **Label Convention**                 **Examples**
  ----------------------------- ------------------------------------ -------------------
  Area                          Common doctrinal name + > Doctrine   Free Speech >
                                suffix when the common name would    Doctrine, Equal
                                collide with a ConstitutionalPro-    Protection >
                                vision label. Otherwise use common   Doctrine,
                                name.                                Individual Rights

  Doctrine                      Descriptive phrase, title case.      Suspect
                                Must not duplicate parent Area       Classification
                                label. Append parent area in         Doctrine,
                                parentheses if needed to             Discriminatory
                                disambiguate.                        Intent Doctrine

  DoctrinalTest                 Proper name + Test, title case.      Central Hudson Test,
                                If no established name, use the      Strict Scrutiny
                                source case name.                    (Equal Protection),
                                                                     Rational Basis Test
                                                                     (Equal Protection)

  Case                          Use short_name field. Party1 v.      New York Times v.
                                Party2 (abbreviated). Full           US, Brandenburg,
                                citation in citation field.          Claiborne Hardware

  ConstitutionalProvision       Citation form only for amendment-    U.S. Const. amend. I
  (amendment/section)           and section-level nodes. Never use   U.S. Const. amend.
                                common name as label.                XIV, § 1

  ConstitutionalProvision       Citation form + parenthetical        U.S. Const. amend. V
  (clause)                      clause name. New in v0.5.            (Due Process Clause)
                                                                     U.S. Const. amend. V
                                                                     (Self-Incrimination
                                                                     Clause)
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **WHY CITATION FORM FOR CONSTITUTIONALPROVISION**                     |
|                                                                       |
| The collision problem: "First Amendment" as a ConstitutionalProvision |
| label collides with "First Amendment > Doctrine" as an Area label.   |
|                                                                       |
| The fix: ConstitutionalProvision nodes use citation form, which is    |
| both unambiguous and the form lawyers use in briefs and opinions.     |
|                                                                       |
| For clause-level nodes, add a parenthetical clause name to           |
| distinguish sibling clauses within the same amendment.               |
|                                                                       |
| The research tool should display the common name in the UI alongside  |
| the citation form --- that is a display concern, not a graph concern. |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**1.2 The > Doctrine suffix rule**

The > Doctrine suffix is appended to an Area label only when the common
name is identical to a ConstitutionalProvision label or would cause
confusion with a Doctrine label.

> * Append > Doctrine when: the Area's common name is also a
> ConstitutionalProvision's common name. Example: "Equal Protection" is
> both an Area and a clause of the 14th Amendment. Suffix: "Equal
> Protection > Doctrine".
>
> * Do not append when: no collision exists. "Individual Rights" has no
> ConstitutionalProvision named "Individual Rights." No suffix needed.
>
> * Graph display rule: in the visualization, the > Doctrine suffix is
> stripped for compactness on the canvas. It appears in full in the
> detail panel and API responses.

**1.3 Handling legitimate same-name concepts**

> * Add a parenthetical qualifier: "Rational Basis (Equal Protection)"
> vs. "Rational Basis (Due Process)"
>
> * For cases with identical short names, append the year: "Smith v.
> Jones (1965)" vs. "Smith v. Jones (1987)"
>
> * For identical names in the same year, append the circuit: "Smith v.
> Jones (1965, 9th Cir.)"

**1.4 Plurality author convention --- New in v0.5**

When a case has no majority opinion (opinion_form: plurality), the
majority_author field should be set to "{Author} (plurality)" rather
than null. This prevents E017 (per_curiam: false but majority_author
null) while accurately representing that no majority opinion exists.

Examples: "Brennan (plurality)" for Frontiero v. Richardson;
"Scalia (plurality)" for Vieth v. Jubelirer.

Do not use this convention for per curiam opinions. Per curiam nodes
must have per_curiam: true and majority_author: null.

**2. Description Standards**

**2.1 Universal description rules**

> * Write in plain English. Avoid jargon not standard in legal practice.
>
> * No advocacy. Describe what the law is, not what it should be.
>
> * Cite at least one primary source for every node.
>
> * Present tense for current doctrine. Past tense for overruled or
> historical doctrine.
>
> * One paragraph for short descriptions. Area and Doctrine nodes may
> have multi-paragraph descriptions if the doctrine is complex.

**2.2 Disputed and contested doctrine**

> * Use status: disputed for a node where the doctrine's current
> validity or content is genuinely contested at the Supreme Court level.
>
> * Use contested: true on individual prongs of a DoctrinalTest where
> there is active Court-level disagreement about that prong's meaning.
>
> * In notes, document both positions: which courts hold each view, the
> leading cases on each side, and the current status.
>
> * Do not present one circuit's rule as the universal rule.
>
> * Post-Dobbs (2022), post-SFFA (2023), and post-Loper Bright (2024)
> doctrinal instability: use status: disputed and document what changed.

**2.3 Holdings**

The holding field is the most consequential prose field in the graph.
Write it as:

> * What the court decided (not what the case was about)
>
> * The governing rule it established or applied
>
> * What that means for future cases in one sentence

Good example: "The constitutional guarantees of free speech do not
permit a state to forbid advocacy of the use of force except where such
advocacy is directed to inciting or producing imminent lawless action
and is likely to produce such action."

Bad example: "The Supreme Court reversed the Ohio Supreme Court's
decision affirming Brandenburg's conviction."

Self-limiting opinions --- New in v0.5: When a per curiam opinion
expressly limits the scope of its holding (e.g., Bush v. Gore: "Our
consideration is limited to the present circumstances"), that
self-limiting language must appear in the holding field. Omitting it
misrepresents the precedential scope of the decision.

**2.4 Fractured decisions**

When no opinion commands a majority, the holding field should state the
judgment (affirmed/reversed) and note that no majority opinion exists.
Describe the controlling opinion and its vote count. Do not overstate
the holding as if a plurality were a majority.

Example structure: "A four-justice plurality held [X]. Justice [Y]
concurred in the judgment on the ground that [Z]. The Court's judgment
was [affirmed/reversed] but no majority opinion issued on [key question]."

**3. Node Type Semantic Tests**

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **THE SEMANTIC TEST FLOWCHART**                                       |
|                                                                       |
| 1. Is it a navigational container that groups related doctrines? ->   |
| Area                                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| (If yes but it also has its own substantive rule: it is a Doctrine   |
| with an Area parent)                                                  |
|                                                                       |
| 2. Is it a substantive rule or analytical framework that lawyers      |
| apply to facts? -> Doctrine                                           |
|                                                                       |
| (If yes and it has numbered prongs with burden notes: go to step 3)  |
|                                                                       |
| 3. Does it have explicitly numbered prongs that function as a         |
| structured checklist? -> DoctrinalTest                                |
|                                                                       |
| (Can the research tool display its prongs as a checklist a lawyer    |
| fills out? If yes: DoctrinalTest)                                     |
|                                                                       |
| 4. Is it a threshold question that determines which test applies? ->  |
| Doctrine with PRECONDITION_TO edge to the gated DoctrinalTest.        |
| New in v0.5.                                                          |
|                                                                       |
| 5. Is it a case, constitutional provision, statute, or regulation? -> |
| appropriate Authority node type                                       |
|                                                                       |
| 6. Does it meet two or more promotion rule conditions (Section 2.8   |
| of Core Ontology)? -> flag for promotion                              |
+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+

**4. Contribution Workflow**

**4.1 Taxonomy spine changes (Layer 1)**

The taxonomy spine requires the highest editorial scrutiny.

> * Create a branch named area/{area-id}
>
> * Add a written justification: why this Area belongs where it does,
> what doctrinal logic places it under its parent
>
> * Run the validator: python validate.py --file your_file.json
>
> * Submit a PR with the justification and at least one authoritative
> secondary source (treatise, Restatement, or law review article)
>
> * Requires sign-off from two reviewers

**4.2 Authority node contributions (Layer 2)**

> * Create a branch named {node-type}/{node-id}
>
> * Add JSON to /data/{node_type}/
>
> * Run validate.py locally
>
> * Run neo4j_import.py with --wipe to verify Neo4j import
>
> * Submit a PR with plain-language description and primary source
> citation
>
> * Requires sign-off from one reviewer

**4.3 Agent pipeline contributions (planned)**

When the agent pipeline is operational, generated nodes require:

> * Passing QA: Semantic (Pydantic / validator), Factual (CourtListener
> cross-reference), and Legal (LLM pressure test against NetworkX
> sandbox)
>
> * Human review of the QA-passing diff before Neo4j Production merge
>
> * Same PR and sign-off requirements as manual contributions

**4.4 Editorial standards**

> * All descriptions in plain English, accurate, and neutral
>
> * No advocacy
>
> * Primary source citation for every node
>
> * Circuit splits explicitly flagged --- never present one circuit's
> rule as universal
>
> * Disputed or recently destabilized doctrine: use status: disputed
>
> * Per curiam opinions: set per_curiam: true, majority_author: null,
> document each separate opinion in opinions[]
>
> * Plurality opinions: set per_curiam: false, majority_author:
> "{Author} (plurality)", document each opinion in opinions[]

**5. ID Conventions**

**5.1 Slug format**

> * lowercase_snake_case only
>
> * No special characters except underscores
>
> * No leading or trailing underscores
>
> * Maximum 80 characters

**5.2 ID patterns by node type**

  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  **Node Type**              **Pattern**                         **Examples**
  -------------------------- ----------------------------------- -------------------------------------------------
  Area                       {doctrinal_name}                    commercial_speech, equal_protection

  Doctrine                   {doctrine_name}                     suspect_classification_doctrine,
                                                                 discriminatory_intent_doctrine

  DoctrinalTest              {test_name}_test                    central_hudson_test, strict_scrutiny_ep_test

  Case                       {party1}_v_{party2}_{year}          loving_v_virginia_1967,
                                                                 washington_v_davis_1976

  ConstitutionalProvision    amendment_{number} for full         amendment_1, amendment_5,
  (amendment)                amendments                          amendment_14_section_1

  ConstitutionalProvision    amendment_{number}_{clause_name}    amendment_5_due_process,
  (clause) New in v0.5       for clause-level nodes              amendment_5_self_incrimination,
                                                                 amendment_14_privileges_immunities
  ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

+-----------------------------------------------------------------------+
| **ID COLLISION POLICY**                                               |
|                                                                       |
| Identical party names + same year: append reporter volume:            |
| smith_v_jones_1973_410us                                              |
|                                                                       |
| Still ambiguous: append court: smith_v_jones_1973_9th_cir             |
|                                                                       |
| IDs are permanent. Once assigned, never change. Even if the label    |
| changes, the ID does not.                                             |
